Note: COBOL Semantic Analyzer for Translation Translation System
Note: Handles COBOL-85 semantic analysis, data structure validation, and business logic verification

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/cobol/cobol_parser.runa" as CobolParser
@Reasoning:
COBOL's four-division structure (IDENTIFICATION, ENVIRONMENT, DATA, PROCEDURE) and its nested sections (FILE, WORKING-STORAGE, LINKAGE) make per-scope state mandatory; current_division/current_section act as the cursor so cross-cutting validations (e.g., a procedure referencing a working-storage item it can't see) work without re-walking. Separating the three section dictionaries lets symbol resolution honor COBOL's visibility rules.
@End Reasoning
Type called "CobolSemanticAnalyzer":
    symbol_table as Integer  Note: Map of data items and procedure names
    current_division as String  Note: Current division being analyzed
    current_section as String  Note: Current section being analyzed
    file_descriptions as Integer  Note: Map of file control entries
    data_definitions as Integer  Note: Map of data item definitions
    procedure_definitions as Integer  Note: Map of paragraph and section definitions
    program_structure as Integer  Note: Map tracking program structure
    error_list as Integer  Note: List of semantic errors
    warning_list as Integer  Note: List of semantic warnings
    level_numbers as Integer  Note: Stack of level numbers for data validation
    working_storage as Integer  Note: Map of working storage items
    linkage_section as Integer  Note: Map of linkage section items
    file_section as Integer  Note: Map of file section items
    copy_books as Integer  Note: Map of included copybooks
End Type

@Reasoning:
A COBOL symbol carries far more semantic weight than in modern languages: PICTURE, USAGE, level number, REDEFINES, and OCCURS all participate in compatibility checks. Tracking division/section on the symbol itself is what allows scope-aware validation in deeply nested PROCEDURE DIVISION code.
@End Reasoning
Type called "CobolSymbol":
    name as String
    symbol_type as String  Note: "data-item", "file", "paragraph", "section", "program"
    data_type as String  Note: "numeric", "alphabetic", "alphanumeric", "group"
    level_number as Integer  Note: 01-49, 66, 77, 88 for COBOL data items
    picture_clause as String  Note: PICTURE specification
    usage_clause as String  Note: DISPLAY, COMPUTATIONAL, PACKED-DECIMAL, etc.
    value_clause as String  Note: Initial value if specified
    occurs_clause as Integer  Note: Number of occurrences (arrays)
    redefines_item as String  Note: Item being redefined
    division as String  Note: Division where symbol is defined
    section as String  Note: Section where symbol is defined
    line_number as Integer
    column_number as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
A data item record captures everything needed for both layout (byte_length, decimal_positions, is_signed) and hierarchy (parent_item, child_items, is_group_item). The level_number drives the hierarchy reconstruction COBOL is famous for: items with higher numbers nest under lower-numbered ancestors until another lower-numbered sibling appears.
@End Reasoning
Type called "CobolDataItem":
    name as String
    level_number as Integer
    picture_clause as String
    usage_clause as String
    value_clause as String
    occurs_count as Integer
    parent_item as String
    child_items as Integer  Note: List of subordinate items
    byte_length as Integer  Note: Computed storage size
    decimal_positions as Integer  Note: Number of decimal places
    is_signed as Integer  Note: 1 if signed, 0 if unsigned
    is_group_item as Integer  Note: 1 if group item, 0 if elementary
End Type

@Reasoning:
COBOL files are richer than POSIX files: organization (SEQUENTIAL/INDEXED/RELATIVE) and access mode (SEQUENTIAL/RANDOM/DYNAMIC) interact (e.g., RANDOM on a SEQUENTIAL file is illegal), and INDEXED files require a record_key. Storing the SELECT clause text alongside lets the validator point at the user's original wording in error messages.
@End Reasoning
Type called "CobolFileDescription":
    name as String
    organization as String  Note: SEQUENTIAL, INDEXED, RELATIVE
    access_mode as String  Note: SEQUENTIAL, RANDOM, DYNAMIC
    record_key as String  Note: Primary key for indexed files
    file_status as String  Note: Status field name
    block_contains as Integer  Note: Block size
    record_contains as Integer  Note: Record size
    select_clause as String  Note: Original SELECT statement
End Type

@Reasoning:
Fresh per-analysis containers avoid cross-file bleed; we also create a level_numbers stack here (not a dict) because COBOL group-item nesting is intrinsically last-in-first-out as the parser walks 01 -> 02 -> 03 -> ... and pops back when a sibling level appears.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_cobol_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create new COBOL semantic analyzer instance

    Let analyzer be a value of type CobolSemanticAnalyzer with
        symbol_table as proc create_dict,
        current_division as "",
        current_section as "",
        file_descriptions as proc create_dict,
        data_definitions as proc create_dict,
        procedure_definitions as proc create_dict,
        program_structure as proc create_dict,
        error_list as proc create_list,
        warning_list as proc create_list,
        level_numbers as proc create_stack,
        working_storage as proc create_dict,
        linkage_section as proc create_dict,
        file_section as proc create_dict,
        copy_books as proc create_dict

    Note: Initialize COBOL built-in features
    proc initialize_cobol_builtins from analyzer

    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The dispatch table covers all 25+ COBOL statement and section nodes; the size of the Match reflects COBOL's verbosity (each verb has its own statement form) and the importance of validating each in its own context (MOVE has different rules from COMPUTE which has different rules from PERFORM). Otherwise -> analyze_children ensures unknown nodes never skip sub-analysis.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
Input AST is untrusted; per-statement validators emit errors via add_semantic_error without aborting the analyzer, so a single malformed statement cannot prevent error reporting on the rest of the program.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "analyze_cobol_ast" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform complete semantic analysis of COBOL AST

    Let node_type be proc get_ast_node_type from ast

    Match node_type:
        When AST_PROGRAM from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_program with analyzer, ast
        When AST_IDENTIFICATION_DIVISION from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_identification_division with analyzer, ast
        When AST_ENVIRONMENT_DIVISION from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_environment_division with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DATA_DIVISION from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_data_division with analyzer, ast
        When AST_PROCEDURE_DIVISION from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_procedure_division with analyzer, ast
        When AST_FILE_SECTION from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_file_section with analyzer, ast
        When AST_WORKING_STORAGE_SECTION from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_working_storage_section with analyzer, ast
        When AST_LINKAGE_SECTION from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_linkage_section with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DATA_ITEM from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_data_item with analyzer, ast
        When AST_MOVE_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_move_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_ADD_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_add_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_SUBTRACT_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_subtract_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_MULTIPLY_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_multiply_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DIVIDE_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_divide_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_COMPUTE_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_compute_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_IF_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_if_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_PERFORM_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_perform_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_CALL_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_call_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_DISPLAY_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_display_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_ACCEPT_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_accept_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_OPEN_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_open_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_CLOSE_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_close_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_READ_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_read_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_WRITE_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_write_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_EVALUATE_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_evaluate_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_GO_TO_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_go_to_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_STOP_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_stop_statement with analyzer, ast
        When AST_EXIT_STATEMENT from CobolParser:
            Return proc analyze_exit_statement with analyzer, ast
        Otherwise:
            Return proc analyze_children with analyzer, ast
    End Match
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL-85 mandates IDENTIFICATION DIVISION and PROCEDURE DIVISION (others are optional). We track presence flags during the single child-walk so the post-walk validation reports each missing division individually with one error each. ENVIRONMENT/DATA are not flagged because their absence is legal for trivial programs.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_program" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze complete COBOL program structure

    Note: COBOL programs must have all four divisions
    Let has_identification be 0
    Let has_environment be 0
    Let has_data be 0
    Let has_procedure be 0

    Note: Analyze each division
    Let child_count be proc get_ast_child_count from ast
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get_ast_child with ast, index
        Let child_type be proc get_ast_node_type from child

        Match child_type:
            When AST_IDENTIFICATION_DIVISION from CobolParser:
                Set has_identification to 1
                proc analyze_cobol_ast with analyzer, child
            When AST_ENVIRONMENT_DIVISION from CobolParser:
                Set has_environment to 1
                proc analyze_cobol_ast with analyzer, child
            When AST_DATA_DIVISION from CobolParser:
                Set has_data to 1
                proc analyze_cobol_ast with analyzer, child
            When AST_PROCEDURE_DIVISION from CobolParser:
                Set has_procedure to 1
                proc analyze_cobol_ast with analyzer, child
            Otherwise:
                proc analyze_cobol_ast with analyzer, child
        End Match

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate program structure
    If has_identification is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Missing IDENTIFICATION DIVISION", ast
    End If

    If has_procedure is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Missing PROCEDURE DIVISION", ast
    End If

    Note: Perform cross-division validation
    proc validate_program_consistency from analyzer

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The DATA division sets analyzer.current_division so child validators (analyze_data_item, file-section validators) can tag every symbol with its division of origin. validate_data_structure_consistency runs once after all sections are absorbed so inter-section checks (e.g., REDEFINES targeting the wrong section) see the complete picture.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_data_division" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze DATA DIVISION with complete data structure validation

    Set analyzer.current_division to "DATA"

    Note: Process each section in DATA DIVISION
    Let child_count be proc get_ast_child_count from ast
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get_ast_child with ast, index
        proc analyze_cobol_ast with analyzer, child
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate data structure consistency
    proc validate_data_structure_consistency from analyzer

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Level numbers are constrained by the COBOL-85 spec to 01-49 (regular hierarchy), 66 (RENAMES), 77 (independent elementary), or 88 (condition name). The dual-condition check (range OR special) reflects exactly that disjunction; rejecting out-of-range values catches the most common COBOL parse-tolerance error. PICTURE/USAGE/VALUE/OCCURS each go to dedicated validators because their syntaxes are independent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_data_item" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze COBOL data item with complete validation

    Let data_item be a value of type CobolDataItem with
        name as proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "name",
        level_number as proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "level",
        picture_clause as proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "picture",
        usage_clause as proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "usage",
        value_clause as proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "value",
        occurs_count as proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "occurs",
        parent_item as "",
        child_items as proc create_list,
        byte_length as 0,
        decimal_positions as 0,
        is_signed as 0,
        is_group_item as 0

    Note: Validate level number
    If data_item.level_number is less than 1 or data_item.level_number is greater than 49:
        If data_item.level_number is not equal to 66 and data_item.level_number is not equal to 77 and data_item.level_number is not equal to 88:
            proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Invalid level number", ast
        End If
    End If

    Note: Validate PICTURE clause
    If data_item.picture_clause is not equal to "":
        proc validate_picture_clause with analyzer, data_item.picture_clause, ast
        proc compute_data_item_size with analyzer, data_item
    End If

    Note: Validate USAGE clause
    If data_item.usage_clause is not equal to "":
        proc validate_usage_clause with analyzer, data_item.usage_clause, ast
    End If

    Note: Validate VALUE clause
    If data_item.value_clause is not equal to "":
        proc validate_value_clause with analyzer, data_item, ast
    End If

    Note: Handle OCCURS clause (arrays)
    If data_item.occurs_count is greater than 0:
        proc validate_occurs_clause with analyzer, data_item, ast
    End If

    Note: Determine if group or elementary item
    proc determine_item_type with analyzer, data_item, ast

    Note: Add to appropriate section
    proc add_data_item_to_section with analyzer, data_item

    Note: Validate level number hierarchy
    proc validate_level_hierarchy with analyzer, data_item, ast

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
MOVE supports multiple targets ("MOVE A TO B C D"); each target gets its own compatibility check because COBOL's MOVE rules vary with both source AND each target type. The source-existence check short-circuits because all targets share the same source, so reporting once is correct.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_move_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze MOVE statement with type compatibility checking

    Let source_field be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "source"
    Let target_fields be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "targets"

    Note: Validate source field exists
    If proc symbol_exists with analyzer, source_field is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Undefined source field in MOVE", ast
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get source field information
    Let source_info be proc get_symbol_info with analyzer, source_field

    Note: Validate each target field
    Let target_count be proc get_list_size from target_fields
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than target_count:
        Let target_field be proc get_list_item with target_fields, index

        If proc symbol_exists with analyzer, target_field is equal to 0:
            proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Undefined target field in MOVE", ast
        Otherwise:
            Let target_info be proc get_symbol_info with analyzer, target_field
            proc validate_move_compatibility with analyzer, source_info, target_info, ast
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COMPUTE requires a numeric target (you cannot COMPUTE into an alphabetic field). We check existence before type so an undefined target yields the more useful "undefined" error rather than a type error against a stale handle.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_compute_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze COMPUTE statement with arithmetic expression validation

    Let target_field be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "target"
    Let expression be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "expression"

    Note: Validate target field exists and is numeric
    If proc symbol_exists with analyzer, target_field is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Undefined target field in COMPUTE", ast
        Return 0
    End If

    Let target_info be proc get_symbol_info with analyzer, target_field
    If proc is_numeric_field with target_info is equal to 0:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Non-numeric target in COMPUTE", ast
    End If

    Note: Validate arithmetic expression
    proc validate_arithmetic_expression with analyzer, expression, ast

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL IF blocks have separate THEN and ELSE statement lists with no terminator inside the AST (the parser already handles END-IF); we therefore analyze each list as an independent unit. validate_conditional_expression handles the condition shape (class-conditions, relation-conditions, complex-conditions).
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_if_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze IF statement with condition validation

    Let condition be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "condition"
    Let then_statements be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "then_statements"
    Let else_statements be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "else_statements"

    Note: Validate condition expression
    proc validate_conditional_expression with analyzer, condition, ast

    Note: Analyze then statements
    If then_statements is not equal to 0:
        proc analyze_statement_list with analyzer, then_statements
    End If

    Note: Analyze else statements
    If else_statements is not equal to 0:
        proc analyze_statement_list with analyzer, else_statements
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
PERFORM has four forms (simple, TIMES, UNTIL, VARYING) sharing a common target-procedure attribute; we validate the procedure reference once and then conditionally validate the form-specific clauses (numeric for TIMES, conditional for UNTIL) only when present, so a simple PERFORM never triggers a numeric/conditional validation against an absent expression.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_perform_statement" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze PERFORM statement with procedure reference validation

    Let target_procedure be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "target"
    Let perform_type be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "type"
    Let times_expression be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "times"
    Let until_condition be proc get_ast_attribute with ast, "until"

    Note: Validate target procedure exists
    If target_procedure is not equal to "":
        If proc procedure_exists with analyzer, target_procedure is equal to 0:
            proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Undefined procedure in PERFORM", ast
        End If
    End If

    Note: Validate PERFORM TIMES expression
    If times_expression is not equal to "":
        proc validate_numeric_expression with analyzer, times_expression, ast
    End If

    Note: Validate PERFORM UNTIL condition
    If until_condition is not equal to "":
        proc validate_conditional_expression with analyzer, until_condition, ast
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The FILE SECTION holds FD entries, but file names must also appear in ENVIRONMENT DIVISION's SELECT clause; we cross-check during FD analysis rather than later because the file name is available here without re-traversing. has_select_statement returning false is a warning (not error) because some preprocessors emit FD entries with the SELECT in a separate copybook.
@End Reasoning
Process called "analyze_file_section" takes analyzer as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Analyze FILE SECTION with file description validation

    Set analyzer.current_section to "FILE"

    Note: Process each file description
    Let child_count be proc get_ast_child_count from ast
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get_ast_child with ast, index
        proc analyze_cobol_ast with analyzer, child

        Note: Validate file has corresponding SELECT statement
        Let file_name be proc get_ast_attribute with child, "name"
        If proc has_select_statement with analyzer, file_name is equal to 0:
            proc add_semantic_warning with analyzer, "File without SELECT statement", child
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
PICTURE syntax has specific invariants: S must be the first character, V may appear at most once, and 9 (numeric) cannot mix with X/A (alpha). We walk the string character-by-character so the error messages point at the exact violation rather than a generic "bad PICTURE". The repetition factor "9(5)" branches to a sub-validator because nested parens require their own parser.
@End Reasoning
@Performance_Hints:
PICTURE strings are typically short (<32 chars); a linear walk is appropriate. Branching on Match is faster than a dispatch table for this small character set.
@End Performance_Hints
Process called "validate_picture_clause" takes analyzer as Integer, picture as String, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate COBOL PICTURE clause syntax and semantics

    If picture is equal to "":
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Empty PICTURE clause", ast
        Return 0
    End If

    Let picture_length be length of picture
    Let index be 0
    Let has_digits be 0
    Let has_alpha be 0
    Let has_decimal be 0

    Note: Parse PICTURE clause character by character
    While index is less than picture_length:
        Let char be proc char_at with picture, index

        Match char:
            When "9":
                Set has_digits to 1
            When "X":
                Set has_alpha to 1
            When "A":
                Set has_alpha to 1
            When "V":
                If has_decimal is equal to 1:
                    proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Multiple decimal points in PICTURE", ast
                End If
                Set has_decimal to 1
            When "S":
                If index is not equal to 0:
                    proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "S must be first character in PICTURE", ast
                End If
            When "(":
                Note: Handle repetition factor (e.g., 9(5))
                proc validate_repetition_factor with analyzer, picture, index, ast
            Otherwise:
                Note: Check for other valid PICTURE characters
                If proc is_valid_picture_char with char is equal to 0:
                    proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Invalid character in PICTURE clause", ast
                End If
        End Match

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate PICTURE consistency
    If has_digits is equal to 1 and has_alpha is equal to 1:
        proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Mixed numeric and alphabetic in PICTURE", ast
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL's MOVE compatibility matrix is asymmetric: numeric->alphabetic is forbidden, but numeric->alphanumeric is permitted with formatting (de-edit -> edit). Each combination is handled in a dedicated branch rather than a 2D matrix so the diagnostics name the actual source/target types in user-facing terms. Group moves take a separate path because they're byte-copy operations not subject to type checks.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_move_compatibility" takes analyzer as Integer, source as Integer, target as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate COBOL MOVE statement type compatibility

    Let source_type be proc get_data_type from source
    Let target_type be proc get_data_type from target
    Let source_picture be proc get_picture_clause from source
    Let target_picture be proc get_picture_clause from target

    Note: COBOL MOVE rules are complex and depend on data types
    Match source_type:
        When "numeric":
            If target_type is equal to "alphabetic":
                proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Cannot move numeric to alphabetic", ast
            Otherwise If target_type is equal to "alphanumeric":
                Note: Numeric to alphanumeric is allowed with formatting
                proc check_numeric_to_alphanumeric_move with analyzer, source, target, ast
            End If
        When "alphabetic":
            If target_type is equal to "numeric":
                proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Cannot move alphabetic to numeric", ast
            End If
        When "alphanumeric":
            If target_type is equal to "numeric":
                proc check_alphanumeric_to_numeric_move with analyzer, source, target, ast
            End If
        When "group":
            Note: Group moves are always allowed (elementary moves)
            proc validate_group_move with analyzer, source, target, ast
    End Match

    Note: Check size compatibility
    proc check_move_size_compatibility with analyzer, source, target, ast

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Arithmetic validation recurses down a binary tree (left, right, operator) so deeply nested COMPUTE expressions are checked structurally rather than via string parsing. Identifiers must resolve to numeric fields; non-numeric refs short-circuit with a precise error. Literal nodes terminate the recursion without further checks because all numeric literals are arithmetically valid.
@End Reasoning
Process called "validate_arithmetic_expression" takes analyzer as Integer, expression as Integer, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Validate COBOL arithmetic expression

    Let expr_type be proc get_ast_node_type from expression

    Match expr_type:
        When AST_BINARY_OPERATION from CobolParser:
            Let left_operand be proc get_ast_child with expression, 0
            Let right_operand be proc get_ast_child with expression, 1
            Let operator be proc get_ast_attribute with expression, "operator"

            proc validate_arithmetic_expression with analyzer, left_operand, ast
            proc validate_arithmetic_expression with analyzer, right_operand, ast

            Note: Validate operator is arithmetic
            proc validate_arithmetic_operator with analyzer, operator, ast

        When AST_IDENTIFIER from CobolParser:
            Let field_name be proc get_ast_attribute with expression, "name"
            If proc symbol_exists with analyzer, field_name is equal to 0:
                proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Undefined field in expression", ast
            Otherwise:
                Let field_info be proc get_symbol_info with analyzer, field_name
                If proc is_numeric_field with field_info is equal to 0:
                    proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Non-numeric field in arithmetic expression", ast
                End If
            End If

        When AST_NUMERIC_LITERAL from CobolParser:
            Note: Numeric literals are always valid in arithmetic expressions
            Return 1

        Otherwise:
            proc add_semantic_error with analyzer, "Invalid expression in arithmetic context", ast
    End Match

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL's figurative constants (ZERO/SPACE/HIGH-VALUE/etc.) and intrinsic functions (CURRENT-DATE/LENGTH/NUMVAL/etc.) are pre-registered so user code references resolve without "undefined" errors. Singular and plural forms (ZERO/ZEROS/ZEROES) are registered separately because COBOL treats them as distinct identifiers, though they denote the same value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "initialize_cobol_builtins" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Initialize built-in COBOL features and functions

    Note: Add figurative constants
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "ZERO", "numeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "ZEROS", "numeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "ZEROES", "numeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "SPACE", "alphanumeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "SPACES", "alphanumeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "HIGH-VALUE", "alphanumeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "HIGH-VALUES", "alphanumeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "LOW-VALUE", "alphanumeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "LOW-VALUES", "alphanumeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "QUOTE", "alphanumeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "QUOTES", "alphanumeric"
    proc add_figurative_constant with analyzer, "ALL", "alphanumeric"

    Note: Add intrinsic functions
    proc add_intrinsic_function with analyzer, "CURRENT-DATE"
    proc add_intrinsic_function with analyzer, "LENGTH"
    proc add_intrinsic_function with analyzer, "NUMVAL"
    proc add_intrinsic_function with analyzer, "NUMVAL-C"
    proc add_intrinsic_function with analyzer, "UPPER-CASE"
    proc add_intrinsic_function with analyzer, "LOWER-CASE"
    proc add_intrinsic_function with analyzer, "REVERSE"
    proc add_intrinsic_function with analyzer, "MAX"
    proc add_intrinsic_function with analyzer, "MIN"
    proc add_intrinsic_function with analyzer, "SUM"

    Return 1
End Process

Note: Helper processes for COBOL semantic analysis

@Reasoning:
Errors are structured dicts so the downstream diagnostics formatter can sort by line/column and group by severity; the line/column come from the AST node so the user sees a precise pointer into their source.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, message as String, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add semantic error with location information

    Let error be a value of type Dictionary[String, Any] with
        "message" as message,
        "line" as proc get_ast_line with ast,
        "column" as proc get_ast_column with ast,
        "severity" as "error"

    proc add_to_list with analyzer.error_list, error
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Warnings share the error record shape but route to a separate list so callers can suppress warnings without losing error semantics; both records carry severity so a future merge into a single diagnostic stream is trivial.
@End Reasoning
Process called "add_semantic_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, message as String, ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Add semantic warning with location information

    Let warning be a value of type Dictionary[String, Any] with
        "message" as message,
        "line" as proc get_ast_line with ast,
        "column" as proc get_ast_column with ast,
        "severity" as "warning"

    proc add_to_list with analyzer.warning_list, warning
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor exposes the error list rather than the analyzer field directly so the underlying representation can later change (e.g., to a deduped set) without breaking callers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_semantic_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return list of semantic errors
    Return analyzer.error_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Warning accessor mirrors the error accessor so a single consumer pattern handles both streams.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_semantic_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return list of semantic warnings
    Return analyzer.warning_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symbol resolution walks the four COBOL visibility scopes in order (working-storage, file-section, linkage-section, procedure-names); the order matters for the human-perceived "nearest definition" but here every dict is independent so any order would resolve correctly. We short-circuit on first hit to keep average lookup at O(1) for typical programs where most refs are in working-storage.
@End Reasoning
Process called "symbol_exists" takes analyzer as Integer, symbol_name as String returns Integer:
    Note: Check if symbol exists in any scope

    Note: Check working storage
    If proc dict_contains with analyzer.working_storage, symbol_name is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Check file section
    If proc dict_contains with analyzer.file_section, symbol_name is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Check linkage section
    If proc dict_contains with analyzer.linkage_section, symbol_name is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Check procedure names
    If proc dict_contains with analyzer.procedure_definitions, symbol_name is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A field is numeric if its PICTURE contains 9 OR its USAGE is one of the explicit numeric clauses (COMP/COMPUTATIONAL/PACKED-DECIMAL/BINARY). We check PICTURE first because that's the more common case in business code, but both checks must be performed because a field can be USAGE COMP with no PICTURE (BINARY items in some dialects).
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_numeric_field" takes field_info as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if field is numeric based on PICTURE clause

    Let picture be proc get_dict_value with field_info, "picture_clause"
    Let usage be proc get_dict_value with field_info, "usage_clause"

    Note: Check for numeric PICTURE patterns
    If proc contains with picture, "9" is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Check for numeric USAGE clauses
    If usage is equal to "COMPUTATIONAL" or usage is equal to "COMP" or
       usage is equal to "PACKED-DECIMAL" or usage is equal to "BINARY":
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Storage size depends on USAGE: DISPLAY is one byte per PICTURE character, COMP is platform-dependent binary, PACKED-DECIMAL is half-byte per digit plus sign nibble, BINARY follows the BIN field width. Each computation is a separate function because the rules don't reuse machinery. OCCURS multiplies the result at the end because OCCURS applies to the item's own size, not its constituents.
@End Reasoning
Process called "compute_data_item_size" takes analyzer as Integer, data_item as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compute storage size of COBOL data item

    Let picture be data_item.picture_clause
    Let usage be data_item.usage_clause
    Let size be 0

    Note: Parse PICTURE clause to determine size
    If usage is equal to "DISPLAY" or usage is equal to "":
        Set size to proc compute_display_size from picture
    Otherwise If usage is equal to "COMPUTATIONAL" or usage is equal to "COMP":
        Set size to proc compute_computational_size from picture
    Otherwise If usage is equal to "PACKED-DECIMAL":
        Set size to proc compute_packed_decimal_size from picture
    Otherwise If usage is equal to "BINARY":
        Set size to proc compute_binary_size from picture
    End If

    Note: Apply OCCURS clause
    If data_item.occurs_count is greater than 0:
        Set size to size multiplied by data_item.occurs_count
    End If

    Set data_item.byte_length to size
    Return size
End Process

@Reasoning:
The 24-byte dictionary header reserves three 8-byte slots (data, size, capacity); entries are appended via set_dict_value which grows the data pointer separately, keeping create_dict O(1) and decoupled from the dict implementation's growth policy.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_dict" returns Integer:
    Note: Create dictionary for storage
    Return proc memory_allocate from Layout with 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
The 16-byte list header (data pointer + size) suffices for an empty list; growing it is deferred to add_to_list which resizes lazily. Most COBOL analyzers create many small lists that stay empty (e.g., child_items on elementary data), so cheap construction matters.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_list" returns Integer:
    Note: Create list for storage
    Return proc memory_allocate from Layout with 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
The level_numbers stack tracks COBOL's hierarchy as the parser descends and ascends data items; 16 bytes (top pointer + size) mirrors the list header because the stack is implemented as a list with push/pop semantics. A dedicated constructor signals intent at call sites.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_stack" returns Integer:
    Note: Create stack for context management
    Return proc memory_allocate from Layout with 16
End Process